─────────────────── Problem 3/5  —  Algebra  [Level 2] ───────────────────

Problem:
Let \[f(x) =
\begin{cases}
3x + 5 &\text{if }x<-3, \\
7-4x&\text{if }x\ge -3.
\end{cases}
\]Find $f(-10)$.

Ground truth answer: -25


▶ Single-Shot

To find $f(-10)$, we need to determine which case applies for $x=-10$.
The first case is $x < -3$. Since $-10 < -3$, we use the first case.
The second case is $x \ge -3$. Since $-10$ is not greater than or equal to $-3$, we do not use the second case.

So, for $x=-10$, we use the formula $f(x) = 3x + 5$.
Substitute $x=-10$ into the formula:
$f(-10) = 3(-10) + 5$
$f(-10) = -30 + 5$
$f(-10) = -25$

The final answer is $\boxed{-25}$.

